<section xml:id="section-projective">
    <title>The Finite Projective Plane</title>
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-projectiveaxioms">
      <title>Axioms and Duality</title>
      <definition xml:id="def-projectiveplane">
        <p>
          A <em>finite projective plane</em> of order <m>n</m> (<m>n\geq 2</m>) is a model that satisfies the Axioms <xref ref="axiom-linesize"/>, 
          <xref ref = "axiom-notbelong"/>, <xref ref = "axiom-existsline"/>, <xref ref = "axiom-twopoint"/> 
          and the following additional Axioms:
        </p>

        <axiom xml:id="axiom-pintersect">
          <p>
            Every pair of distinct lines intersect at at least one point.
          </p>
        </axiom>

        <axiom xml:id="axiom-psize">
          <p>
            There is at least one line <m>L</m> containing exactly <m>n+1</m> points.
          </p>
        </axiom>

        


      </definition>

      <problem>
        <p>
          If a model satisfies <xref ref="def-projectiveplane"/> do the theorems proven in  <xref ref="section-plane"/> hold for it?
        </p>
      </problem>

      

      <problem>
        <p>
          Show that the grid found in <xref ref="activity-buildplane"/> satisfies <xref ref="def-projectiveplane"/>. 
           What would the points and lines be?
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Does the model found in <xref ref="problem-euclid"/> satisfy <xref ref="def-projectiveplane"/>?  Why or why not?
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Does the model found in <xref ref="problem-hyperbolic"/> satisfy <xref ref="def-projectiveplane"/>?  Why or why not?
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Does the model found in <xref ref="problem-fano"/> satisfy <xref ref="def-projectiveplane"/>?  Why or why not?
        </p>
      </problem>

      <p>
        For the following proofs, some of them are really just rewording of known axioms/results.  Some of them are more involved.
      </p>

      <problem xml:id="dual-linesize">
        <p>
          Show that for each point <m>P</m>, there are at least two lines which contain <m>P</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem xml:id ="dual-notbelong">
        <p>
          Show that for each point <m>P</m>, there is least one line which does not contain <m>P</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem xml:id="dual-existsline">
        <p>
          Show that there is at least one point <m>P</m>.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem xml:id="dual-twopoint">
        <p>
          Given any two lines <m>L, M</m>, they intersect at exactly one point.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem xml:id="dual-pintersect">
        <p>
          Given any two points <m>P, Q</m>, there is at least one line containing them both.
        </p>
      </problem>

      

      <problem xml:id="dual-psize">
        <p>
          There is at least one point <m>P</m> contained by exactly <m>n+1</m> lines.
        </p>
        <hint>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  By <xref ref="axiom-psize"/> there is a line <m>L</m> that has <m>n+1</m> points. 
                   Label these points <m>P_1, P_2,\ldots, P_{n+1}</m>.
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>
            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  Explain why there must be a point <m>A</m> that is not contained by <m>L</m>. 
                  (What if every point was contained by <m>L</m>?  What bad thing would happen?).
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>
            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  Explain why for each <m>P_i</m>, there is a line containing it and <m>A</m>.
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>
            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  Can we show that none of the lines we just found can be the same line?  
                  (What if <m>\overleftrightarrow{P_i A}=\overleftrightarrow{P_i B}</m>?  What bad thing would happen?)
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>

            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  How do we know these are all the lines which contain <m>A</m>? 
                   (Let <m>M</m> be some line containing <m>A</m>.  Why does <m>M</m> have to be one of the lines we just found?)
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>

            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  Conclude that <m>A</m> is (one of) the point(s) which is contained by exactly <m>n+1</m> lines.
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>
            
          </ol>
        </hint>
      </problem>

      <problem xml:id="problem-duality">
        <task>
          <p>
            Compare <xref ref="axiom-linesize"/> and <xref ref="dual-linesize"/>.  What do you notice?
          </p>
        </task>
        <task>
          <p>
            Compare <xref ref="axiom-notbelong"/> and <xref ref="dual-notbelong"/>.  What do you notice?
          </p>
        </task>
        <task>
          <p>
            Compare <xref ref="axiom-existsline"/> and <xref ref="dual-existsline"/>.  What do you notice?
          </p>
        </task>
        <task>
          <p>
            Compare <xref ref="axiom-twopoint"/> and <xref ref="dual-twopoint"/>.  What do you notice?
          </p>
        </task>
        <task>
          <p>
            Compare <xref ref="axiom-pintersect"/> and <xref ref="dual-pintersect"/>.  What do you notice?
          </p>
        </task>
        <task>
          <p>
            Compare <xref ref="axiom-psize"/> and <xref ref="dual-psize"/>.  What do you notice?
          </p>
        </task>
        <task>
          <p>
            What does all this tell you about the relationship between <em>points</em> and <em>lines</em> in finite projective planes?
          </p>
        </task>
      </problem>

    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-projectivecounting">
      <title>Counting points and lines</title>

      

      <problem>
        <p>
          If a finite projective plane has <m>k</m> points, how many lines do you suppose it has?  Why?  
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Show that a finite projective plane has at least one collection of 4 lines, no three of which intersect at the same point.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Show that a finite projective plane has at least one collection of 4 points, no three of which line on the same line. 
           (You can show this directly, or what does the discussion in <xref ref="problem-duality"/> tell us?)
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem xml:id="problem-pointcontain">
        <p>
          Given <em>any</em> line <m>L</m> containing <m>x</m> points, and <em>any</em> point <m>A</m>  not
          contained in <m>L</m>, <m>A</m> is contained in exactly <m>x</m> lines.  (Can we repurpose parts of the proof of <xref ref="dual-psize"/>?)
        </p>
      </problem>
      
      <problem >
        <p>
          Given <em>any</em> point <m>P</m> contained in <m>x</m> lines, and <em>any</em> line <m>M</m> not
          containing  <m>P</m>, <m>M</m> contains exactly <m>x</m> points.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Show that given any two points <m>A, B</m>, there is a line containing neither <m>A</m> nor <m>B</m>.
        </p>  
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Show that given any two lines <m>L, M</m>, there is a point contained in neither <m>L</m> nor <m>M</m>.
        </p>  
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Show that if <m>L</m> is any line containing <m>n+1</m> points, and <m>P</m> is a point not contained in 
          <m>L</m>, then <m>P</m> is contained in exactly <m>n+1</m> lines.  
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Show that if <m>P</m> is any point contained in <m>n+1</m> lines, and <m>L</m> is a line not containing 
          <m>P</m>, then <m>L</m> is contains  exactly <m>n+1</m> points.  
        </p>
      </problem>



      <problem>
        <p>
          Show that for <em>every</em> point in a finite projective plane, there exactly <m>n+1</m> lines containing that point.
        </p>
        <hint>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  There is a line <m>L</m> with <m>n+1</m> points.  Why?  Call these points <m>P_1, P_2, \ldots, P_{n+1}</m>.
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>
            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  Let <m>P</m> be a point not on <m>L</m>, why are there exactly <m>n+1</m> lines containing <m>P</m>?  
                  See <xref ref="problem-pointcontain"/>.
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>

            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  Now suppose instead that <m>P</m> were on <m>L</m>.  There must be some <m>Q</m> not on <m>L</m>.  Why?
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>

            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  Show that there is a line <m>M</m> that contains neither <m>P</m> nor <m>Q</m>.
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>

            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  <m>Q</m> is contained in exactly <m>n+1</m> lines, why?  Call these lines <m>L_1, L_2, \ldots, L_{n+1}</m>.
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>

            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  Do these lines <m>L_i</m> intersect <m>L_i</m>?  Why or why not?  Can two different lines <m>L_i, L_j</m> intersect <m>M</m> at the same point?
                  Why or why not?  Call the point where <m>L_i</m> intersects <m>M</m> <m>A_i</m>.
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>
            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  Does <m>M</m> contain any other points besides the <m>A_i</m>?  Why or why not?  How many points does <m>M</m> have?
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>

            <li>
              <hint>
                <p>
                  So <em>FINALLY</em>, why is <m>P</m> contained in exactly <m>n+1</m> lines?
                </p>
              </hint>
            </li>

            
            
          </ol>
        </hint>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Show that <em>every</em> line contains <m>n+1</m> points.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          How many points does a finite projective plane of order <m>n</m> have?
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          How many lines does a finite projective plane of order <m>n</m> have?
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          What order is the projective plane found in <xref ref="problem-fano"/>?  Verify that it has the right number of points and lines.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          What order is the projective plane found in <xref ref="activity-buildplane"/>?  Verify that it has the right number of points and lines.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <problem>
        <p>
          Draw a projective plane of order 4.
        </p>
      </problem>

      
      
    </subsection>

       
      

    
